Review: Enjoyed this a lot more than expected, but that could be the thrill of seeing something on holiday overseas.
I felt bored the entire first half. Then I enjoyed some battle scenes. Then I felt bored again.

I can appreciate this was a beautifully made film, tackling a very relevant topic, but I did find it a little dull for the first hour. In the second hour it really picked up - especially through conversations about race that were, oftentimes, unintentionally/intentionally hilarious. The town meeting was by far the best scene.

Last year I found my worst film of the year in February. I may have beaten that record this year. This is some Tubi trash you don’t even want to try to suffer through. This was the most cliched and trope filled nonsense ever. The acting is horrific and the sound editing, filming and scene transitions are bizarre. Literally it’s been filmed on multiple very different quality cameras that snap noticeably between each other. Half the sound is an echoey…

There are definitely some absolutely gorgeously shot scenes, and there were some very hard to watch moments that felt very well done (the avalanche, the crash). But mostly I just didn’t really find this gripping me the way I expected.

I liked this, but I thought I would love it. The premise starts out well, especially when you learn what’s in the Christmas Card, but I felt like it never really hit those emotional moments I expected. Instead it felt a little lacklustre.

I’ve sat with this one a couple of days, not sure how to articulate what I thought.I can see why this may be divisive for some, and it may be the definition of “trust the process” with the themes. I will admit I was off-put at first but the performance of someone who seemed intellectually disabled, and even though that was clarified, I was still off-put by the amount of sexual desire towards a woman who had the brain…
There was a lot to love about this. The set up and drama when it unfolded, sound, some of the incredible shots achieved and the general tone dipping its toes into comedy very gently.
I very much annoyed most of this. It’s a bit of a character piece, and each character was definitely interesting.
Reminds me of being 18. Carefree, fancy free and deeply in trouble. I just never realised it when it was happening. That always came later.
